Design Documentation – Key Choices & Justifications
1. Embedding Model: all-MiniLM-L6-v2 (sentence-transformers)

Choice justification:
Very fast inference (~20–80 ms per chunk on CPU) → critical for low-latency on Render free tier
384-dimensional embeddings → good balance between quality and storage/indexing cost in Chroma
Strong performance on semantic similarity for English policy text (trained on large paraphrase datasets)
Open-source, no API calls → zero cost & no external dependency

Alternatives considered:
Larger models (e.g. all-mpnet-base-v2, e5-large) → better accuracy but 3–10× slower & more memory
OpenAI text-embedding-3-small → higher quality but costs money + adds latency/network round-trip


2. Chunking Strategy

Choice: Simple fixed-size chunking (~600–800 characters) with ~100–150 character overlap
Justification:
Policy documents are mostly structured text (sections, bullet points, short paragraphs) → fixed-size works well without complex semantic splitting
Overlap ensures context continuity across chunk boundaries (important for sentences split by chunk edge)
Keeps average chunk count low (16 items in your DB) → fast retrieval even with top_k=20

Alternatives considered:
RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter (LangChain) → more natural but slower & more complex for small corpus
Sentence-based splitting → risk of very short chunks in bullet-heavy policies


3. Retrieval Parameter: top_k = 20 (with optional reranking)

Choice justification:
20 provides enough candidates to capture relevant passages even with noisy queries
Still small enough to keep context under typical LLM token limits (~8k–16k tokens with free models)
Reranking enabled by default (cosine similarity re-sort) → improves precision without huge cost

Trade-off:
Higher k → better recall, but increases context length → slower LLM generation & higher cost on paid models
Lower k (8–12) → faster, but risk of missing key passages → used in low-latency ablation


4. Prompt Format

Choice: Strict instruction prompt with explicit rulestextYou are the NSR Policy Assistant. Answer the user question using ONLY the context below. 
Be clear, professional, and friendly.
- If the answer is not in the context, say "I could not find relevant information."
- Do not invent or assume information.
- Reference document names when possible.

Context:
{context}

Question:
{query}
Justification:
"ONLY the context" + "Do not invent" → maximizes groundedness (your eval showed 100%)
"Be clear, professional, and friendly" → matches corporate policy tone
Explicit fallback instruction → prevents hallucinations when no relevant chunks are found
Simple structure → works reliably even with weaker free models


5. Vector Store: Chroma (persistent on disk)

Choice justification:
Lightweight, fully local (no external service) → zero cost & fast startup
PersistentClient with disk storage → survives Render redeploys (via attached volume)
Supports metadata filtering & simple HNSW indexing → sufficient for small corpus (~16 items)
Easy Python API → minimal code overhead

Alternatives considered:
Pinecone / Weaviate → managed but requires API key + free tier limits
FAISS → faster pure in-memory but no persistence out of the box


Summary of Design Philosophy

Priorities: High groundedness & citation accuracy (achieved 100% in eval) + zero external LLM/embedding cost + reasonable speed on free hosting
Trade-offs accepted: Higher latency (cold starts + free LLM) in exchange for zero running cost & perfect faithfulness
Future improvements: Faster hosting (Railway/Railway hobby), quantized embeddings, or local LLM (Ollama) if moving off Render